{
  "texts": [
    "Neither of these prototypical models can explain the evidence.",
    "Instead, our results show a shift in the judge-specic component of decision-making, holding law and political aliation constant.",
    "On this particular point, the best previous evidence was Bonica et al. (2019), who show in the context of the U.S. Supreme Court that changes in the ideology of selected clerks sometimes shift a justice's votes.",
    "Beyond that, the literature has largely attended to legal rules determining outcomes (Kornhauser, 1992; Gennaioli and Shleifer, 2007b), or else invariant judge characteristics such as political aliation, average decision tendencies, campaign donation tendencies, or demographics (e.g.",
    "Cameron, 1993; Martin and Quinn, 2002; Epstein et al., 2013; Ash et al., 2021; Bonica and Sen, 2021)."
  ]
}